data.content: When was Notre Dame Cathedral reopened?

Notre Dame Cathedral reopened on December 7, 2024. This reopening followed restoration work after a fire in April 2019. The fire destroyed the cathedral's spire and roof and caused extensive interior damage.
Who led this ceremony?

The ceremony on December 7 was attended by numerous current and former heads of state and government, as well as senior officials of international organizations. Nearly 170 bishops from France and around the world participated in the service at the Archbishop's invitation. One priest from each of the 106 parishes in the Diocese of Paris also attended.
Who was present at this ceremony?

Numerous current and former heads of state and government, along with senior officials of international organizations attended the ceremony. Other attendees included John Kerry, Elon Musk, Marine Le Pen, and François Bayrou. Nearly 170 bishops, priests, and parishioners also participated in the service.
what he said in his speech

In his speech, President Macron thanked those involved in the restoration of Notre Dame Cathedral. The apostolic nuncio to France, Archbishop Celestino Migliore, read a message from Pope Francis, who expressed his joy at joining "in spirit and prayer" with those at the cathedral.
did he also participate in the celebrations the next day?

Yes, President Macron and his wife attended the inaugural mass the next day, which was held on December 8. Other heads of state and government and senior French politicians were also present. The mass was presided over by Archbishop Ulrich, who consecrated the new high altar.
